Valve goes multicore

For many programmers, writing multithreaded applications that take full …

Jeremy Reimer - 11/6/2006, 9:00 AM

The future

Valve plans to integrate this technology into the Source engine, and slowly deliver content that makes use of multicore processors. Gabe mentioned that even if a million people upgrade to quad-core CPUs in a year (which Valve believes is not beyond the realm of possibility given its hardware surveys) those numbers weren't enough to pay for putting a box in retail stores that would require this hardware for best performance. However, Valve is in a unique position thanks to Steam, whereby they can deliver small bits of content directly to consumers at much lower cost to the company. While this technology probably won't make it into Episode 2, look for a repeat of the Valve Lost Coast HDR demo. Eventually, all Valve products will support this technology and the company has plans to backport it to older games such as the original Half-Life 2 (Newell wouldn't talk about Half-Life 3). Valve intends to distribute their frameworks to all of its licensees as well as making it available to the mod community.

As far as console ports go, Gabe mentioned that Valve is already putting their hybrid threading technology to good use for their Xbox 360 projects, but could not comment about its applicability to the PS3 as they were not doing any PS3 ports themselves and had no PS3 systems in their building at the time. One of the Valve programmers did mention that the PS3's architecture is not quite as suited to their frameworks due to its asymmetric approach and the fact that the SPU (Synergistic Processing Units) could not directly access main memory.

A question was asked about supporting executing game code directly on GPUs, an idea that some have considered due to the improvements in GPU speed over the last few years, Valve does not believe that this is the correct approach. GPUs can't natively execute existing x86 code whereas multiple cores can execute it directly, meaning less work for the programmers. As far as writing code for the new physics accelerator cards, Gabe still hasn't ruled out doing something in that area, but he believes that they have not penetrated the market enough to make it a worthwhile venture. In contrast, multiple cores are the present and future of personal computing. Valve is confident that its tools will scale just as well to eight cores and beyond, and should work on both Intel and AMD's multicore offerings (although they haven't done any testing on AMD's upcoming quad-core CPUs yet).

Newell was asked about why the company didn't wait until Vista and DirectX10 to deliver this technology. He replied that this was an orthogonal issue; they wanted to ship as soon as they could, and quad cores are shipping now. Valve hardware surveys show that new CPU adoption rates are very swift with certain members of their audience. Newell wouldn't comment on how Vista and DX10 would affect their technology, saying, "ask me in two weeks."

Conclusions

When questioned about his apparent about-face from bemoaning the necessity of supporting multiple cores to being totally committed to a multicore approach, Newell said that the decision was difficult, and not without its trials and tribulations. Newell believes that the work done at Valve puts the company ahead by as much as two years compared to other game companies, who are just starting to tackle the issue of multithreaded programming.

Newell even talked about a trend he sees happening in the future that he calls the "Post-GPU Era." He predicts that as more and more cores appear on single chip dies, companies like Intel and AMD will add more CPU instructions that perform tasks normally handled by the GPU. This could lead to a point where coders and gamers no longer have to worry if a certain game is "CPU-bound" or "GPU-bound," only that the more cores they have available the better the game will perform. Newell says that if it does, his company is in an even better position to take advantage of it.

So was my prediction about game companies not rushing to support multithreaded code inaccurate? Valve, for one, has done a 180-degree turn on the issue, and it's likely that many other companies will do the same. If anything, I'm happy to have the hard work, dedication, and talent of the gaming industry overturn my original thesis. However, Newell's statements make it clear that jumping over the multiprocessing hurdle is not something that everyone will be able to do. Companieslike Valvethat are committed to making this effort will be able to reap the rewards of doing so, and gamers will surely enjoy the fruit of their labors.
